com.tomtom.speedtools.geometry

Class GeoPoint

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.tomtom.speedtools.geometry.GeoObject
      • com.tomtom.speedtools.geometry.GeoPoint
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    JsonRenderable

    @Immutable
public final class GeoPoint
extends GeoObject
    Geometric point, 2D or 3D. A geometric point is specified in latitude, longitude and an optional elevation. If the elevation is not supplied, it is not assumed to be 0, but it is assumed to be really absent (and will, for example, not be output in string conversions either). Constructor: GeoPoint()

      • getElevationMetersOrNaN

        @Nonnull
public Double getElevationMetersOrNaN()
        Get elevation (in meters), or NaN if the elevation is absent. Note that the return cannot be null (but it can be NaN)! This means you can use this getter in expressions like this: {code} GeoPoint p = p1.getElevationMetersOrNaN() + p2.getElevationMetersOrNan() {code} Using the 'orNan'-getter means 'p' is a valid double, even if 'p1' or 'p2' has no elevation and returns NaN (in which case 'p' will also become NaN). Using the regular getter, you would be forced to checked for 'null' for every elevation.
        Returns:
        Elevation in meters, or NaN if absent. This return value is never null! This allows the caller to "do the math", like adding or averaging elevations, even if they don't exist for all points, because once NaN is used in an expression, the result will be NaN as well.

      • getElevationMeters

        @Nullable
public Double getElevationMeters()
        Get elevation (in meters). Normally, you should probably use getElevationMetersOrNaN().
        Returns:
        Elevation in meters, or null, if no elevation is present.
